        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "feat: expose node-hosted plugin tools",
        "body": "## Summary\n\n- Add dynamic node-hosted plugin/MCP tools so a Gateway on one computer can expose tools registered by connected nodes on other computers.\n- Add `node.pluginTools.update`; node hosts publish their current `registerNodeHostCommand(...agentTool...)` inventory after `hello-ok` and whenever the node-side plugin/MCP inventory changes.\n- Materialize trusted node-host descriptors as normal agent-visible plugin tools, with provider-safe names, `tools.effective` cache invalidation, node online/offline removal, stale-connection checks, and execution through `node.invoke` under the existing node command allowlist policy.\n- Preserve raw node declarations and refresh effective descriptors after Gateway plugin runtime load, so nodes that connect before descriptors are registered still become visible once plugin commands are available.\n- Update Gateway protocol types, Swift generated models, node list/catalog surfaces, SDK/runtime docs, and gateway protocol docs for node-hosted plugin tools.\n\n## Implementation Notes\n\n- Node plugins register node-host commands through `api.registerNodeHostCommand`; optional `agentTool` metadata marks commands as agent-accessible MCP/plugin tools while that node is connected.\n- Gateway normalizes node-provided descriptors against the Gateway plugin registry and node command policy before exposing anything to agents.\n- Connected node tools are tracked in a versioned snapshot, so `tools.effective` updates when nodes publish, disconnect, reconnect, or when Gateway plugin descriptors refresh.\n- The E2E proof script writes a proof plugin dynamically and supports split roles: `gateway`, `node`, `verify`, and `local`.\n\n## Documentation\n\n- `docs/plugins/sdk-overview.md`: documents `api.registerNodeHostCommand(command)` and `agentTool` exposure.\n- `docs/plugins/sdk-runtime.md`: documents node-hosted plugin/MCP descriptor publishing and lifecycle.\n- `docs/gateway/protocol.md`: documents `node.pluginTools.update` and node tool descriptor behavior.\n- `docs/cli/node.md`: documents node plugin tool exposure from `openclaw node run`.\n\n## Verification\n\n- GitHub PR rollup for `bfd9fcac18453ca015a19f9797f4e66a7b72ca69`: 135 passing checks, no pending checks, no failing checks; PR mergeable/clean.\n- Testbox through Crabbox changed gate: `tbx_01ktacn5dpp4qbqp4mh4x9jwvj`, Actions run `26983844938`, `OPENCLAW_CHECK_CHANGED_REMOTE_CHILD=1 OPENCLAW_CHANGED_LANES_RAW_SYNC=1 corepack pnpm check:changed`, exit 0.\n- Focused final Vitest on the pushed head: `node scripts/run-vitest.mjs src/gateway/node-registry.test.ts src/gateway/node-connect-reconcile.test.ts src/gateway/node-command-policy.test.ts src/gateway/server-methods/tools-effective.test.ts src/node-host/runner.test.ts src/tasks/task-flow-registry.store.test.ts`; 3 shards passed, including 14 gateway files / 250 gateway tests, node-host runner tests, and task-flow store tests.\n- Focused lint for the CI lint blocker: `node scripts/run-oxlint.mjs src/tasks/task-flow-registry.store.test.ts`, exit 0.\n- Autoreview: clean after the final rebased cleanup commit; no accepted/actionable findings.\n\n## Real Pond Proof\n\n- AWS Crabbox gateway lease `cbx_83967533d714` in pond `oc-node-tools-1780612217-31184` exposed Gateway port `18789`.\n- Local Mac node hosts connected through the Crabbox pond SSH mesh, forwarding `127.0.0.1:51820` to the AWS Gateway port.\n- Verifier saw two connected node-hosted `pond_echo` MCP tools and invoked both through Gateway `tools.invoke`; outputs came back from local nodes `pond-a` and `pond-b`.\n- Remote Gateway logs showed two node pair approvals, `tools.effective`, two `node.invoke`, and two `tools.invoke` successes.\n- Pond lease was released after proof. The AWS Gateway run exit was from intentional lease release after the successful verifier run.\n",
        "branch": "feat/node-dynamic-plugin-tools",
